user_prompt_template:
As of {as_of}, does {company}'s drawdown look cyclical/sentiment-driven (a temporary, external, or fixable problem — a demand cycle, a regulatory overhang, a leverage problem fixable by refinancing/cost cuts, a manufacturing execution problem in an otherwise-viable business) rather than a structural business breakdown (permanent demand destruction, the core product/service becoming obsolete, an unfixable competitive position)? Score 4 (clearly cyclical/fixable), 2 (unclear/mixed), or 0 (looks structural) — based only on what was true and knowable as of {as_of}.

Company situation:
{company_brief}

As of {as_of}, does {company}'s balance sheet/leverage look reasonable relative to its sector norm (not stretched)? Score 2 (doesn't look stretched), 1 (uncertain/no clear signal), or 0 (looks stretched) — based on P/B ratio, sector, and company description as of {as_of} only.

Company situation:
{company_brief}

P/B ratio (if known): {pb_ratio}

As of {as_of}, does {company}'s sector/theme have a genuine multi-year tailwind (not just a short-term bounce)? Score 4 (genuine multi-year tailwind), 2 (neutral), or 0 (headwind) — based on what was true and knowable as of {as_of}.

Company situation:
{company_brief}

As of {as_of}, does {company}'s description or recent history suggest a real inflection point (new leadership, restructuring, a product cycle) rather than 'waiting for the same thing to eventually work'? Score 3 (real inflection point), 1 (unclear), or 0 (no visible catalyst) — based on what was true and knowable as of {as_of}.

Company situation:
{company_brief}

Given the full scored rubric below for {company} (all other criteria's scores and reasoning), would this position fit this account's stated few-trades-per-quarter, high-conviction style — i.e. is this a name you could hold with real conviction without needing active day-to-day monitoring? Score 2 (fits) or 0 (doesn't fit / would need active monitoring).

Full scored rubric so far:
{full_rubric_results_json}

As of {as_of}, is {company} a top-tier/dominant leader in its specific market domain (clear #1 or #2, durable moat) or at least a solid niche leader (#3-4, real but not airtight moat) — durable enough to be worth holding through a full 10-year cycle regardless of near-term volatility? Or is it sub-scale/commoditized/easily disrupted? Score 5 (dominant leader), 2 (solid niche leader), or 0 (sub-scale/commoditized/disrupted) — based on {company}'s actual market position as of {as_of} only.

